In this Act, unless the context otherwise requires—
'authorized officer' means any officer of the Agency authorized in writing by the Chief Executive under section 7;
'Chief Executive' means the Chief Executive of the National Cyber Security Agency appointed under section 6;
'Committee' means the National Cyber Security Committee established under section 8;
'computer' means an electronic, magnetic, optical, electrochemical, or other data processing device, or a group of such interconnected or related devices, performing logical, arithmetic, storage and display functions, and includes any data storage facility or communications facility directly related to or operating in conjunction with such device or group of such interconnected or related devices;
'cyber security' means the state in which a computer, computer system, network, data, software application, computer program or other configurable computing resource is protected from cyber security threats;
'cyber security incident' means any act or activity carried out without authorization on a computer, computer system, network, data, software application, computer program or other configurable computing resource that jeopardizes or adversely affects its cyber security, including unauthorized access, interference, interception, denial of service, data breach, system compromise or exploitation of vulnerability;
'cyber security risk assessment' means a systematic process for identifying, analyzing and evaluating cyber security risks;
'cyber security service' means a service that is provided for the purpose of protecting or responding to a cyber security threat to a computer, computer system, network, data, software application, computer program or other configurable computing resource, and includes managed security operations centre monitoring service, penetration testing service, cyber security incident response service, and any other service as may be prescribed;
'cyber security service provider' means any person who provides a cyber security service;
'cyber security threat' means any act, omission, activity, or state of affairs that may jeopardize or adversely affect the cyber security of a computer, computer system, network, data, software application, computer program or other configurable computing resource;
'data' means representations of information or concepts that are being prepared or have been prepared in a form suitable for use in a computer;
'national critical information infrastructure' means any computer or computer system, which the disruption, destruction, degradation or compromise of, or unauthorized access to, would have a debilitating impact on the delivery of a service essential to the security, defence, foreign relations, economy, public health, public safety, or public order of Malaysia, or on the ability of the Federal Government or any State Government to carry out its functions effectively;
'NCII entity' means an entity designated as an NCII entity under section 17;
'NCII sector' means any sector specified in the Schedule;
'NCII sector lead' means a Government Entity designated as an NCII sector lead under section 17;
'network' means a system of two or more computers that are interconnected by telecommunications links;
'prescribed' means prescribed by the Minister by regulations made under this Act.

(1) The National Cyber Security Agency shall have the following functions:
(a) to be the national lead agency for cyber security matters;
(b) to advise and coordinate the implementation of cyber security policies;
(c) to develop and implement national cyber security strategies, standards, guidelines, codes of practice and directives;
(d) to monitor, assess and respond to cyber security threats and incidents;
(e) to promote cooperation and coordination on cyber security matters among Government Entities, NCII sector leads and NCII entities;
(f) to promote research and development in cyber security;
(g) to enhance awareness and education on cyber security;
(h) to advise on any matter relating to the cyber security of national critical information infrastructure;
(i) to coordinate with foreign countries and international organizations on cyber security;
(j) to carry out any other functions as may be prescribed.
(2) The Agency shall have all such powers as may be necessary for, or in connection with, or reasonably incidental to, the performance of its functions under this Act.

(1) A committee to be known as the National Cyber Security Committee is established.
(2) The Committee shall consist of the following members:
(a) the Prime Minister, who shall be the Chairman;
(b) the Minister responsible for communications and multimedia;
(c) the Minister responsible for defence;
(d) the Minister responsible for home affairs;
(e) the Chief Secretary to the Government;
(f) the Secretary General of the National Security Council;
(g) the Chief Executive; and
(h) not more than five other members appointed by the Prime Minister.
(3) The Chief Executive shall be the Secretary to the Committee.

(1) The Committee shall have the following functions:
(a) to advise the Government on national cyber security policies, strategies and measures;
(b) to oversee the implementation of national cyber security policies and strategies;
(c) to determine the national critical information infrastructure sectors;
(d) to coordinate responses to cyber security threats and incidents that affect national security;
(e) to promote cooperation and coordination on cyber security among Government Entities;
(f) to carry out any other functions as may be prescribed.
(2) The Committee may establish any sub-committee as it considers necessary to assist in the performance of its functions.

(1) An NCII entity shall—
(a) implement and maintain cyber security measures to protect the national critical information infrastructure;
(b) comply with any standards, codes of practice and directives issued under this Act;
(c) report any cyber security incident to the Chief Executive in accordance with this Act;
(d) conduct or cause to be conducted cyber security risk assessments in accordance with this Act;
(e) conduct or cause to be conducted cyber security audits in accordance with this Act;
(f) provide information as required by the Chief Executive or the NCII sector lead; and
(g) comply with any other duty as may be prescribed.
(2) Failure to comply with subsection (1) shall constitute an offence and the NCII entity shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding five hundred thousand ringgit or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding ten years or to both.

(1) An NCII sector lead shall—
(a) coordinate and monitor the cyber security of national critical information infrastructure in its sector;
(b) develop and recommend codes of practice for its sector;
(c) advise NCII entities in its sector on cyber security matters;
(d) report to the Chief Executive on the state of cyber security in its sector;
(e) assist NCII entities in its sector in complying with this Act; and
(f) comply with any other duty as may be prescribed.
(2) An NCII sector lead may issue guidelines to NCII entities in its sector on matters relating to cyber security.

(1) The Chief Executive may suspend or revoke a licence if the licensee—
(a) has contravened any provision of this Act or any condition of the licence;
(b) has been convicted of any offence involving fraud or dishonesty;
(c) obtained the licence through fraud, misrepresentation or concealment of a material fact;
(d) has ceased to carry on the business of providing cyber security services; or
(e) is a body corporate and is being wound up.
(2) Before suspending or revoking a licence, the Chief Executive shall give the licensee a written notice of his intention to do so and shall give the licensee an opportunity to make representations.
(3) A person aggrieved by a suspension or revocation may appeal to the Minister within thirty days.

(1) A licensee shall—
(a) comply with all conditions of the licence;
(b) maintain the standards of competence, integrity and professionalism in the provision of cyber security services;
(c) maintain the confidentiality of any information obtained in the course of providing cyber security services;
(d) keep and maintain records of all cyber security services provided; and
(e) comply with any directive or guideline issued by the Chief Executive.
(2) A licensee that fails to comply with subsection (1) commits an offence.

(1) If it appears to a Magistrate, upon written information on oath, that there is reasonable cause to believe that any premises are being used, or there is in any premises evidence necessary for the conduct of an investigation under this Act, the Magistrate may issue a warrant authorizing an authorized officer to enter the premises and to search for and seize any computer, computer system, data, document, or other article.
(2) An authorized officer conducting a search under subsection (1) may—
(a) break open any outer or inner door or window;
(b) forcibly enter any premises;
(c) remove by force any obstruction; and
(d) detain any person found in the premises until the search is completed.

Any person who—
(a) refuses any authorized officer access to any premises;
(b) assaults, obstructs, hinders or delays any authorized officer in the exercise of his powers under this Act;
(c) refuses to produce any document, computer, computer system, data or other article when required to do so; or
(d) refuses to answer any question put to him by an authorized officer,
commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding three hundred thousand ringgit or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding five years or to both.

(1) The Minister may make such regulations as may be necessary or expedient for the purpose of carrying out the provisions of this Act.
(2) Without prejudice to the generality of subsection (1), regulations may be made for—
(a) prescribing the forms to be used and the fees to be paid under this Act;
(b) prescribing the procedure for cyber security risk assessments and audits;
(c) prescribing the requirements for notification of cyber security incidents;
(d) prescribing the conditions and procedures for the licensing of cyber security service providers;
(e) prescribing the offences which may be compounded under section 54;
(f) prescribing the classes of cyber security services;
(g) any other matter required to be prescribed under this Act.
(3) Regulations made under this section may prescribe any act or omission in contravention of the regulations to be an offence and may prescribe penalties of a fine not exceeding three hundred thousand ringgit or imprisonment for a term not exceeding five years or to both.
